     "text": [
      "\n",
      "Description of scheme file format\n",
      "---------------------------------\n",
      "\n",
      "   A scheme specifies the overall look of a graph and is defined by a scheme\n",
      "   file.  Each entry in a scheme file specifies the look for a specific\n",
      "   attribute of a specific graph element, such as the color of a symbol or\n",
      "   the size of text.\n",
      "\n",
      "   This information is provided primarily for those creating their own\n",
      "   graphics schemes.  We describe the format of scheme files and the effect\n",
      "   entries in the scheme file have on graphs.  For an overview of graphics\n",
      "   schemes, see [G-4] Schemes intro.\n",
      "\n",
      "\n",
      "Remarks\n",
      "-------\n",
      "\n",
      "   Remarks are presented under the following headings:\n",
      "\n",
      "        Creating your own schemes\n",
      "        What is a scheme-file entry?\n",
      "        Plot entries \n",
      "        Composite entries \n",
      "        Example scheme file\n",
      "        Suggestions\n",
      "\n",
      "   See scheme entries for the full list of scheme file entry definitions, but\n",
      "   first read the rest of this help file.\n",
      "\n",
      "\n",
      "Creating your own schemes\n",
      "-------------------------\n",
      "\n",
      "   Scheme schemename is stored in file scheme-schemename.scheme.  For\n",
      "   example, scheme s2color is stored in file scheme-s2color.scheme.  You can\n",
      "   find where a scheme file is located by typing\n",
      "\n",
      "        . which scheme-schemename.scheme\n",
      "\n",
      "   To create a new scheme, say mine, you need only create a file with the\n",
      "   name scheme-mine.scheme in your PERSONAL directory (see [P] sysdir).  You\n",
      "   should always base your scheme on a scheme shipped with Stata or on\n",
      "   another scheme based on an official scheme shipped with Stata.  You do\n",
      "   that by putting the line\n",
      "\n",
      "        #include schemename\n",
      "\n",
      "   before any scheme-file entries in your scheme.  If you want to base your\n",
      "   scheme on the scheme Stata uses by default when shipped, the line should\n",
      "   read\n",
      "\n",
      "        #include s2color\n",
      "\n",
      "   Graphs drawn with your scheme will start out looking just like those drawn\n",
      "   with s2color, and the entries that you make in your scheme file will serve\n",
      "   as edits to the s2color scheme.\n",
      "\n",
      "   For the adventurous, that may be sufficient information.  Look at the file\n",
      "   containing the s2color scheme - type which scheme-s2color.scheme to locate\n",
      "   that file.  You will find the lines in the file very readable, and you can\n",
      "   often guess what effect a line has.  When you want to change something,\n",
      "   simply create a similar line in your own file and change the style (the\n",
      "   last word on the line) to whatever you prefer; for example, for a color\n",
      "   entry change green to red.  For the less adventurous, read on.\n",
      "\n",
      "\n",
      "What is a scheme-file entry?\n",
      "---------------------------- \n",
      "\n",
      "   Each entry in a scheme file specifies how a particular attribute of a\n",
      "   graph element looks.  For example,\n",
      "\n",
      "        symbolsize matrix medium\n",
      "\n",
      "   specifies that the size of symbols used in scatterplot matrices is to be\n",
      "   medium.  We know this because the first word of the entry specifies the\n",
      "   styletype, or attribute affected; the second word is the graph element, or\n",
      "   the part affected (here matrix is short for scatterplot matrix); and the\n",
      "   third word is the style to be applied to the specific attribute of the\n",
      "   element.\n",
      "\n",
      "   We could change medium to small or large or any of the predefined styles\n",
      "   for markersizestyle, or we could specify a number for the size.  This\n",
      "   number is scaled so that 100 represents the full height of the graph (or\n",
      "   width if the width is smaller than the height); see [G-4] size.  The\n",
      "   available options for each style that may be specified, the 3rd word, are\n",
      "   documented in the tables of entries in scheme entries.\n",
      "\n",
      "   As a second example, we could change the text color for axis titles from\n",
      "   black to red by changing the line,\n",
      "\n",
      "        color axis_title black\n",
      "   to\n",
      "        color axis_title red\n",
      "\n",
      "   The available styles for color entries are the colorstyles, which include\n",
      "   explicit RGB values, rather than just named colors; see [G-4] colorstyle\n",
      "   for more information and a discussion of RGB values.  This means that we\n",
      "   could have changed the entry to\n",
      "\n",
      "        color axis_title \"255 0 0\"\n",
      "\n",
      "   a bright red.  Note that the RGB values and any style using more than one\n",
      "   token or word must be enclosed in quotes.\n",
      "\n",
      "\n",
      "Plot entries\n",
      "------------ \n",
      "\n",
      "   In addition to standard entries, scheme files have many entries for plots.\n",
      "\n",
      "   What is a plot?  When you type\n",
      "\n",
      "        . scatter y1 y2 x\n",
      "\n",
      "   the set of plotted markers for y1 versus x is the first plot and y2 versus\n",
      "   x is the second plot.  The markers for the first plot look different from\n",
      "   those for the second plot -, with perhaps different colors, or sizes, or\n",
      "   both.  With different graph commands, we might have two lines that differ,\n",
      "   or two sets of bars, or two pie slices, but in all cases we refer to these\n",
      "   as plot1 and plot2, and their looks are controlled by pstyles (short for\n",
      "   plot styles); see [G-4] pstyle.  The official scheme files have entries\n",
      "   for 15 plots.\n",
      "\n",
      "   An entry to set the marker size for the second plot might be\n",
      "\n",
      "        symbolsize p2 medium\n",
      "        \n",
      "   where p2 specifies plot2.\n",
      "\n",
      "   As it turns out, most of Stata's official schemes use the same size\n",
      "   markers for all plots.  Rather than having 15 entries to set the same\n",
      "   marker size, we simply omit the plot number and use the following single\n",
      "   entry that applies to all plots:\n",
      "\n",
      "        symbolsize p medium\n",
      "\n",
      "   We saw earlier how to base your own scheme on another scheme, such as the\n",
      "   official s2color scheme, and in that case we must take some care using\n",
      "   just p.  Because s2color defines only one symbolsize for all plots, we\n",
      "   could change the size of all symbols to large by adding the line\n",
      "\n",
      "        symbolsize p large\n",
      "\n",
      "   If s2color had been more specific and included entries to separately\n",
      "   define marker sizes for plot1 - plot15, then those more specific entries\n",
      "   would take precedence over our entry that did not specify a plot number.\n",
      "   We would need to make individual entries for p1, p2, etc., for each plot.\n",
      "\n",
      "   Note that there are many attributes for plot elements, so there are many\n",
      "   plot entries.  In addition to marker size, there are entries for marker\n",
      "   color,\n",
      "\n",
      "        color p1 navy\n",
      "\n",
      "   marker symbol (shape),\n",
      "\n",
      "        symbol p circle\n",
      " \n",
      "   and sets of entries for lines, boxes, and other plot elements.\n",
      "\n",
      "   We pulled these two examples from the s2color scheme, and you can see that\n",
      "   the marker colors are different for each plot, whereas the marker symbols\n",
      "   are all circles.\n",
      "\n",
      "   Plot entries can be even more specific than plot number.  Some entries can\n",
      "   be directed at a particular kind of plot.  For example, the entry\n",
      "\n",
      "        color p3line yellow\n",
      "\n",
      "   will make the third line plot yellow but will not affect the color of\n",
      "   scatters, bars, or other plottypes.  While the s2color scheme does not\n",
      "   take advantage of this, you can create schemes with different colors and\n",
      "   intensities for each plottype -- scatter, line, bar, pie slice, etc.\n",
      "\n",
      " \n",
      "Composite entries\n",
      "----------------- \n",
      "\n",
      "   When we said that each entry specifies a particular attribute, that was an\n",
      "   oversimplification.  Some entries designate how the specific attributes\n",
      "   will be assigned for a collection of attributes for a graph element.  We\n",
      "   will call the entries for these collections composite entries.\n",
      "\n",
      "   Textboxes, for example, are used for titles, captions, and many other\n",
      "   graph text elements.  There are 11 attributes associated with a textbox,\n",
      "   for example, the size of the text, the color of the text, the color of the\n",
      "   background, and more; see [G-4] textboxstyle for the full list.  Changing\n",
      "   a textboxstyle entry, which is a composite entry, can potentially change\n",
      "   all 11 of these attributes.\n",
      "\n",
      "   Let's look at two composite entries for textboxstyles:\n",
      "\n",
      "        textboxstyle axis_title axis_title\n",
      "        textboxstyle title      heading\n",
      "\n",
      "   The first entry specifies that the textboxstyle for axis titles is to be\n",
      "   the axis_title style, which seems like a good default.  Similarly, the\n",
      "   second line specifies that the textboxstyle for graph titles is to be the\n",
      "   heading style.\n",
      "\n",
      "   We could make axis titles look just like graph titles by changing the\n",
      "   specified textboxstyle of the first entry from axis_title to heading:\n",
      "\n",
      "        textboxstyle axis_title heading\n",
      "\n",
      "   Now, all axis titles will look like graph titles - they will have the same\n",
      "   text size, the same text color, etc.\n",
      "\n",
      "   Note that changes to composite entries can interact with the effects of\n",
      "   other entries.  In section 2, we changed the color of axis title text by\n",
      "   changing the color axis_title black entry to color axis_title red.  Now\n",
      "   that the composite textboxstyle entry for axis titles no longer specifies\n",
      "   the axis_title style, but rather the heading style, our color change will\n",
      "   have no effect.  We would need to change the color heading black entry to\n",
      "   color heading red to change the color of axis titles.  This would also\n",
      "   change the color of graph titles because the two now share the heading\n",
      "   textboxstyle.\n",
      "\n",
      " \n",
      "Example scheme file\n",
      "-------------------\n",
      "\n",
      "   As discussed in section 1, you can create your own schemes by creating a\n",
      "   file in your PERSONAL director called scheme-schemename.scheme.  Let's\n",
      "   look at a very simple example of such a scheme and name the scheme simple.\n",
      "\n",
      "\n",
      "        --- Begin scheme-simple.scheme ------------------------\n",
      "        #include s2color\n",
      "        color background  white\n",
      "        --- End scheme-simple.scheme --------------------------\n",
      "\n",
      "   This scheme is based on the s2color scheme; and we can tell that because\n",
      "   of the #include s2color line (see section 1). It changes only one thing --\n",
      "   the background color is set to white.  If we use simple by including\n",
      "   scheme(simple) option on our graph command (see [G-4] Schemes intro for\n",
      "   more ways to set the scheme), then the graph region will no longer be\n",
      "   bluish gray, but will be white.  Any other graph element that references\n",
      "   the background color will also be white.\n",
      "\n",
      "   Now, let's look at a slightly more complicated example, which we will call\n",
      "   mine.\n",
      "\n",
      "        --- Begin scheme-mine.scheme --------------------------\n",
      "        * This is our better demonstration scheme.\n",
      "        * We should probably go on to describe it further here.\n",
      "\n",
      "        *! version 1.0.0   12nov2004\n",
      "\n",
      "        #include s2color\n",
      "\n",
      "        color background  white\n",
      "        color major_grid  \"200 200 200\"\n",
      "\n",
      "        color p1          \"  0 255   0\"\n",
      "        color p2          magenta\n",
      "\n",
      "        anglestyle vertical_tick    horizontal\n",
      "\n",
      "        clockdir   legend_position  4\n",
      "        numstyle   legend_cols      1\n",
      "        linestyle  legend           none\n",
      "        margin     legend           \"5 0 0 0\"\n",
      "        --- End scheme-mine.scheme ----------------------------\n",
      "\n",
      "   The first two lines are simply comments to help us identify our scheme\n",
      "   later.  Note that in scheme files, comments can only be entered as entire\n",
      "   lines and the lines must begin with a \"*\".  The third line is just a fancy\n",
      "   comment that identifies the version number of our scheme and the date it\n",
      "   was last updated.\n",
      "\n",
      "   The line #include s2color includes the entire contents of the official\n",
      "   s2color scheme in our scheme.  Again, this is just the starting point for\n",
      "   our changes.\n",
      "\n",
      "   As in simple, the line color background white sets the background color to\n",
      "   white.  Similarly, the line color major_grid \"200 200 200\" specifies that\n",
      "   grid lines be drawn in a light shade of gray.  Here we are using an RGB\n",
      "   value rather than a named colorstyle; see section 2.  For more entries\n",
      "   relating to grid lines, see scheme grids.\n",
      "\n",
      "   The next two entries,\n",
      "\n",
      "        color p1          \"  0 255   0\"\n",
      "        color p2          magenta\n",
      "\n",
      "   change how the first two plots look.  The first entry changes the color of\n",
      "   the first plot to a bright green using the RGB value \"0 255 0\".  Note that\n",
      "   the extra spacing is not required in the RGB value; it is only there to\n",
      "   make the entries align nicely in the file.  The second entry changes the\n",
      "   color of the second plot to magenta using the named colorstyle magenta.\n",
      "\n",
      "   The anglestyle vertical_tick horizontal entry changes the angle of text\n",
      "   used to label the ticks on the y axis (designated by vertical_tick) to be\n",
      "   horizontal so that they are not turned \"sideways\" as they are in the\n",
      "   s2color scheme.  See scheme axes for more entries relating to axes.\n",
      "\n",
      "   The last four entries change where and how legends are displayed.  The\n",
      "   clockdir legend_position 4 entry moves the legend from its default\n",
      "   position at the bottom of the graph to 4 o'clock - the right of the graph\n",
      "   and aligned with the bottom of the graph.  numstyle legend_cols 1 changes\n",
      "   the default number of columns in the legend from 2 to 1, while\n",
      "   linestyle legend none turns off the outlining around the legend.  Finally,\n",
      "   margin legend \"5 0 0 0\", designates a small margin, 5% of the graph size,\n",
      "   to the left of the legend with no margin (0) to the right, top, or bottom.\n",
      "   Find out more about these entries and other legend settings at scheme\n",
      "   legends.\n",
      "\n",
      "   In 10 lines, we have changed quite a bit about how graphs drawn with our\n",
      "   scheme will look.  You can click here to create a copy of\n",
      "   scheme-mine.scheme in your current working directory, and then you can\n",
      "   draw some graphs using the new scheme.  For starters try\n",
      "\n",
      "        . sysuse auto\n",
      "        . scatter trunk turn weight, scheme(s2color)\n",
      "        . scatter trunk turn weight, scheme(mine)\n",
      "\n",
      "   and compare the difference.  Try drawing some other bar graphs or others\n",
      "   with the new scheme.\n",
      "\n",
      "\n",
      "Suggestions\n",
      "-----------\n",
      "\n",
      "   The first and best suggestion is to try it.  The base scheme file for\n",
      "   graphics, scheme-s2color.scheme has over 1,700 entries.  Because composite\n",
      "   entries often change the effect of other entries (see section 4), the\n",
      "   entry descriptions in scheme entries at best indicate what will happen if\n",
      "   you base your new scheme on s2color; if you base it on another scheme, you\n",
      "   may need to experiment to get the desired effects.\n",
      "\n",
      "   It is also a good idea to build your new scheme in small steps while\n",
      "   checking the results on a graph.  Draw a graph that has all the elements\n",
      "   you want to control: perhaps axes, legends, or even the third scatter\n",
      "   plot.  Then create your scheme file and place a #include statement to base\n",
      "   your scheme on an existing scheme.  Now redraw your graph using your new,\n",
      "   but empty, scheme using the scheme(your_scheme) option.  Now add one entry\n",
      "   to your scheme, issue the discard command, redraw the graph by reissuing\n",
      "   the graph command, and observe the result.  Then, make changes to the\n",
      "   entry, if desired; or, move on to the next element you want to change.\n",
      "   This is how scheme-mine.scheme was created.  In particular, we did not\n",
      "   know exactly how all the changes to the legends would look, and we altered\n",
      "   several entries after seeing the initial results.\n",
      "\n",
      "   It is critical that you issue the discard command each time before you\n",
      "   reissue your graph command.  discard reinitializes the graphics system,\n",
      "   and that includes clearing the graphics scheme.  If you do not type\n",
      "   discard, graph will note that you are using the same scheme each time and\n",
      "   will use the already loaded scheme - ignoring the changes you made in the\n",
      "   scheme file.\n",
      ". "
     ]
